{"timestamp": "2026-03-19T18:07:41.223894", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Glutamate\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Glutamate. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nPrebiotic Synthesis of Glutamate in Early-Earth and Astrochemical Contexts\nScope and chemical framing\nGlutamate (2-aminopentanedioate) is chemically distinctive among proteinogenic amino acids because it is dicarboxylic and because, in extant core metabolism, it sits at the main \u201cnitrogen entry\u201d bottleneck: reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate is the canonical route of ammonia assimilation, with glutamate then serving as the dominant amino-group donor for broad amino-acid biosynthesis via transamination. [1]\nFor prebiotic network design, that framing suggests a practical decomposition: (i) build or supply a C5 dicarboxylate carbon skeleton in a form that is hydrolytically plausible (most often \u03b1-ketoglutarate or its \u201cmasked\u201d equivalents), (ii) install nitrogen via reductive amination or via nitrile-based amino-acid synthesis (Strecker-like or Bucherer\u2013Bergs-like), and (iii) manage unavoidable competing reactions (carbonyl reduction \u2192 hydroxyacids, photofragmentation, decarboxylation, etc.) by matching steps to environments and catalysts that can coexist. [2]\nKnown prebiotic synthesis routes supported by experiments\nMultiple experimentally supported or seriously proposed routes reach glutamate under plausibly prebiotic regimes; they differ mainly in how nitrogen is introduced and which upstream precursor is assumed.\nH\u2082-driven reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate over nickel and meteoritic catalysts\nA direct metabolic analogue has been demonstrated by Harpreet Kaur[3] et al. (2024, Chem[4]): \u03b1-ketoglutarate + NH\u2084\u207a + H\u2082 \u2192 glutamate under mild aqueous conditions catalyzed by nickel-based materials or ground meteorites, producing a mixture of glutamate and hydroxyketoglutarate (from competing carbonyl reduction). The system is explicitly framed as a \u201cprebiotic Krebs-cycle analog\u201d that links carbon-fixation-like ketoacid generation to amino-acid formation. [5]\nGeoelectrochemical FeS/Fe\u2070 assemblages in alkaline hydrothermal settings\nNorio Kitadai[6] et al. (2019, Science Advances[7]) report that electrochemically generated FeS\u2013Fe\u2070 assemblages (FeS partially electroreduced to metal; \u201cFeS_PERM\u201d) strongly promote ketoacid reductive amination at alkaline pH. In their system, pyruvate \u2192 alanine and \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate proceed \u201cnearly completely\u201d at pH ~9.6 with concentrated ammonia, in a setup explicitly motivated by alkaline hydrothermal vent geoelectrochemistry and mineral redox/pH gradients. [8]\nNeutral-pH \u201cphosphoro\u2013Strecker\u201d access to glutamate aminonitrile from succinic semialdehyde\nKathryn Ashe[9] et al. (2019, Communications Chemistry[10]) demonstrate a neutral-pH Strecker variant in which aldehydes react with HCN and diamidophosphate (DAP) to yield N\u2011phosphoro\u2011aminonitriles at pH ~7 (bypassing the classical need for high pH to keep ammonia unprotonated). Crucially for glutamate, the aldehyde 4\u2011oxobutanoic acid (i.e., succinic semialdehyde bearing a terminal carboxylate) yields N\u2011phosphoro\u2011glutamic acid aminonitrile in 88% yield at neutral pH. Subsequent hydrolysis can be steered by pH: acidic hydrolysis gives the corresponding aminonitrile, whereas alkaline hydrolysis gives N\u2011phosphoro amino acids. [11]\nThis route is especially important for early-Earth plausibility because it explicitly addresses the \u201cpH incompatibility\u201d between many HCN-derived systems chemistry environments and classical Strecker requirements. [11]\nBucherer\u2013Bergs-like conversion of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate using cyanide and DAP\nSunil Pulletikurti[12] et al. (2022, Nature Chemistry[13]) show that \u03b1-ketoacids can be converted to \u03b1-amino acids via a Bucherer\u2013Bergs pathway (hydantoin formation \u2192 hydrolysis), using cyanide plus prebiotically motivated ammonia sources. Their supplementary data document an explicit glutamate case starting from \u03b1-ketoglutarate with DAP and NaCN, proceeding through 5\u2011carboxyethyl hydantoin and N\u2011carbamoyl glutamate to glutamate upon heating. Under one optimized condition (0.5 M bicarbonate buffer, pH 8.5), glutamate was reported in 19% yield after staged room-temperature incubation and heating; under a second condition (pH 6 in water at 80\u202f\u00b0C), glutamate was 21% yield after 7 days. [14]\nSpark-discharge (volcanic plume / atmosphere\u2013water interface) synthesis yielding glutamate among products\nArchived prebiotic-atmosphere discharge residues analyzed with modern methods by Eric T Parker[15] et al. (2011, Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences[16]) include glutamic acid among the detected amino acids in an H\u2082S-rich spark discharge experiment designed to model \u201clocalized volcanic plume chemistry.\u201d Their figures report amino-acid molar ratios relative to glycine, showing glutamate present at roughly the 10\u207b\u00b2 level relative to glycine in the H\u2082S experiment (order-of-magnitude read from the plotted molar ratios). [17]\nMechanistically, spark discharge experiments are closely tied to aqueous-phase HCN + aldehyde generation and subsequent Strecker-type aminonitrile formation/hydrolysis, a linkage analyzed in detail by Stanley L Miller[18] (1957, Biochimica et Biophysica Acta[19]). [20]\nUV-driven ZnS surface photochemistry enabling reversible \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u21c4 glutamate interconversion\nA surface-photochemical \u201cenzyme-like\u201d model is provided by Wei Wang[21] et al. (2012, Chemical Communications[22]; electronic supplementary information). Under UV irradiation with ZnS suspensions, alkaline pH (~9), and ammonium chloride, glutamate can be produced from \u03b1-ketoglutarate in percent-level yields, with yields sensitive to ZnS preparation (reported glutamate yields across ZnS variants ~0.6% to 7.4%). [23]\nThe broader ZnS concept is extended in the associated literature to a reversible redox \u201chomeostasis\u201d between \u03b1-oxoacids and \u03b1-amino acids under shallow-water photochemical conditions. [24]\nUpstream photoredox provision of \u03b1-ketoglutarate from \u03b1-hydroxyglutarate in cyanosulfidic settings\nA key constraint for any glutamate route is the availability of \u03b1-ketoglutarate. Dougal J Ritson[25] (2021, Science Advances[7]) demonstrates that UV photolysis of hydrosulfide (HS\u207b) can oxidize \u03b1-hydroxy carboxylates \u2192 \u03b1-oxo carboxylates under pH ~6.5 in phosphate buffer, explicitly producing \u03b1-ketoglutarate from \u03b1-hydroxyglutarate. Reported yields include ~20% \u03b1-ketoglutarate after 2.5 h irradiation (with minor succinate formation) and, when cyanide is present, large capture into \u03b1-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin (~45%) alongside smaller free \u03b1-ketoglutarate. [26]\nThis route does not itself aminate \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate, but it provides a quantitatively demonstrated upstream feedstock pathway compatible with HCN/HS\u207b photoredox networks that also generate amino-acid precursors. [26]\nFormate-based reduction claims and their critique\nA frequently discussed \u201csimple reductant\u201d hypothesis is that formate reduces \u03b1-ketoglutarate plus ammonia to glutamate; Quinn Maughan[27] and Stanley L. Miller[28] (1999, Origins of Life and Evolution of the Biosphere[29]) directly challenge this, concluding that \u201cformate reduction, if any, is small\u201d under the reported conditions and that observed glutamate formation proceeds mainly via a different process involving oxidative decarboxylation coupled to a second \u03b1-ketoglutarate. [30]\nExtraterrestrial and parent-body synthesis as a glutamate source term\nGlutamic acid has been measured in carbonaceous meteorites (evidence for nonbiological synthesis in asteroidal aqueous alteration environments), for example in the Murchison meteorite analysis by Michael H Engel[31] and Bartholomew Nagy[32] (1982, Nature[33]). While not an \u201cEarth environment\u201d route, meteoritic glutamate supports the plausibility of multi-step aqueous organic synthesis networks that include dicarboxylic amino acids.\nKey intermediates, precursors, and network branch points\nAcross the literature, glutamate production clusters around two carbon-skeleton precursors that act as major branch points into multiple prebiotic networks:\n\u03b1-ketoglutarate is the dominant precursor in reductive-amination and Bucherer\u2013Bergs styles of chemistry. It is (i) directly aminated to glutamate in metal-catalyzed H\u2082 systems, (ii) a target of HS\u207b/UV oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxyglutarate (providing an upstream, non-enzymatic source), and (iii) a node within broader Krebs-cycle-like abiotic interconversion schemes (including succinate semialdehyde bypass topologies). [34]\nSuccinic semialdehyde / 4-oxobutanoic acid is the aldehyde precursor that maps naturally onto a Strecker logic for glutamate: aldehyde \u2192 (iminium) \u2192 aminonitrile \u2192 hydrolysis \u2192 amino acid. The phosphoro\u2013Strecker work gives unusually direct experimental support for this exact aldehyde leading to a glutamate-family aminonitrile under neutral pH. [11]\nImportant intermediate \u201ccontrol knobs\u201d that recur across routes include:\nCyanohydrins and aminonitriles. In nitrile-based amino-acid synthesis, cyanohydrins can be both (a) stepping stones (cyanide addition to carbonyl), and (b) kinetic traps that compete against amination/hydrolysis depending on ammonia activity and pH. The cyanosulfidic network analysis explicitly emphasizes cyanohydrin/aminonitrile equilibria as a function of pH and ammonia availability. [26]\nN-phosphoro-aminonitriles (phosphoro\u2013Strecker). These species are unusually stable at near-neutral pH compared with many free aminonitriles and allow pH-programmable downstream transformations (acid \u2192 aminonitrile; base \u2192 N-phosphoro amino acid). They represent a potentially crucial bridge between \u201cHCN photochemistry worlds\u201d and more metabolism-like amino-acid inventories. [11]\nHydantoin and carbamoyl intermediates (Bucherer\u2013Bergs). In the \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate Bucherer\u2013Bergs case, the key intermediates reported are 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin and N-carbamoyl glutamate, with glutamate emerging upon prolonged heating/hydrolysis. [35]\nHydroxy-acid side products (reductive amination routes). Metal-catalyzed H\u2082 systems commonly co-produce hydroxyacids by direct carbonyl reduction, creating a selectivity problem but also furnishing additional \u201cmetabolic-like\u201d redox couples and feedstocks for later oxidation back to ketoacids. [36]\nReaction mechanisms and conditions by route\nReductive amination routes\nThe mechanistic core is formation of an imine/iminium from the \u03b1-ketoacid plus NH\u2083/NH\u2084\u207a followed by reduction (hydride transfer equivalents sourced from H\u2082 on metal surfaces, or by coupled redox processes at mineral interfaces). In aqueous systems, a persistent competing channel is simple carbonyl reduction to the \u03b1-hydroxyacid. [37]\nIn the nickel/H\u2082 work of Harpreet Kaur[3] et al. (2024, Chem), \u03b1-ketoacids at ~30 mM react in water at ~22\u202f\u00b0C, pH ~8, under H\u2082 (~5 bar) with NH\u2084HCO\u2083 as ammonia source, using catalysts including Ni/SiO\u2082\u2013Al\u2082O\u2083 (10 mol% Ni), Pd/C (1 mol% Pd), or ground iron meteorites. For \u03b1-ketoglutarate specifically, the reported combined yield (glutamate + hydroxyketoglutarate) is 34% (Ni catalyst; amino:hydroxy 45:55), 54% (Pd; 91:9), and 71% (meteorite; 23:77). Converting these ratios gives approximate glutamate yields of ~15% (Ni), ~49% (Pd), and ~16% (meteorite) under their stated conditions, with the remainder as hydroxyketoglutarate. [36]\nIn the FeS_PERM geoelectrochemical work (Kitadai et al., 2019, Science Advances), reductive aminations are run at room temperature (23\u201325\u202f\u00b0C) for ~48 h in sealed serum bottles, with alkaline pH maintained at ~9.6 by strong base plus concentrated ammonium salt (reported as 1 M NH\u2084Cl mixed with NaOH to yield high NH\u2083). Under these conditions, \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2192 glutamate proceeds \u201cnearly completely\u201d in the presence of FeS_PERM, while related steps (e.g., oxaloacetate \u2192 malate at near-neutral pH 6.5) are assigned to different pH \u201czones,\u201d motivating a vent-precipitate microcompartment/pH-gradient environment. [8]\nZnS photochemical amination adds a different reducing-power source: photogenerated electrons in a semiconductor conduction band reduce an iminium/imino intermediate, while a sacrificial hole scavenger maintains charge balance. In the ZnS experiments (Wang et al., 2012, Chemical Communications ESI), a typical run uses 2 mmol ZnS, 1 mmol \u03b1-ketoacid, 100 mmol NH\u2084Cl, pH adjusted to ~9, optional Na\u2082SO\u2083 (10 mmol) as hole scavenger, in 50 mL aqueous suspension under argon, irradiated by a 500 W mercury\u2013xenon lamp. Reported glutamate yields from \u03b1-ketoglutarate are catalyst-preparation dependent, ranging from 0.6\u202f\u00b1\u202f0.1% up to 7.4\u202f\u00b1\u202f0.7%. [23]\nStrecker-type nitrile chemistry and its neutral-pH variants\nClassical Strecker synthesis proceeds via (i) imine formation from an aldehyde and ammonia, (ii) cyanide addition to yield an \u03b1-aminonitrile, and (iii) nitrile hydrolysis to the amino acid. In spark discharge systems, HCN and aldehydes/ketones are generated as primary intermediates, and Miller\u2019s mechanistic analysis argues that Strecker chemistry in the aqueous phase can account for observed amino-acid accumulation during week-scale runs. [38]\nThe phosphoro\u2013Strecker system (Ashe et al., 2019, Communications Chemistry) changes the nitrogen source logic: DAP acts as an \u201cammonia surrogate\u201d enabling efficient Strecker-like carbonyl \u2192 aminonitrile construction at neutral pH (~7). The work explicitly contrasts its pH optimum with the classical Strecker requirement (near the pK_a of ammonia), and demonstrates strong yields for aldehydes bearing polar/charged groups. For glutamate specifically, 4\u2011oxobutanoic acid \u2192 N\u2011phosphoro\u2011glutamate aminonitrile is reported at 88% yield at neutral pH. Acidic vs alkaline hydrolysis then routes to different downstream products (aminonitriles vs N\u2011phosphoro amino acids). [11]\nThe spark-discharge/volcanic-plume proxy analysis (Parker et al., 2011, PNAS) provides direct evidence that glutamate can appear among the amino-acid inventory produced by discharge-driven atmospheric mixtures including H\u2082S and CO\u2082. The paper reports molar ratios relative to glycine; glutamate is present at low but clearly detectable abundance (order 10\u207b\u00b2 of glycine in the H\u2082S experiment). A caution noted in the same study is that some low-abundance amino acids (including aspartate and glutamate) show L-enrichment, which the authors interpret as consistent with trace terrestrial contamination in those low-level components, even while other amino acids are racemic. [17]\nBucherer\u2013Bergs (hydantoin) conversion of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate\nPulletikurti et al. (2022, Nature Chemistry) show in their supplementary procedures that \u03b1-ketoglutarate can be carried into glutamate via a hydantoin-mediated pathway (Bucherer\u2013Bergs logic), using cyanide plus DAP under buffered aqueous conditions. Under one \u201coptimized\u201d condition (0.5 M bicarbonate buffer, pH 8.5), the protocol is staged: 21 days at room temperature to form the hydantoin derivative, then 14 days at 80\u202f\u00b0C to generate glutamate. The reported yields include ~96% 5\u2011carboxyethyl hydantoin after the room-temperature stage and 19% glutamate after the heating stage (with substantial hydantoin remaining). Under pH 6 water at 80\u202f\u00b0C for 7 days, glutamate is 21% yield. [39]\nMechanistically, this class of route can be viewed as an alternative to direct reductive amination that (i) tolerates different pH regimes, (ii) stores carbon and nitrogen in relatively stable cyclic intermediates, but (iii) imposes energetic/time requirements for ring opening and hydrolysis, with incomplete conversion in demonstrated conditions. [35]\nPhotochemical oxidation routes that provision \u03b1-ketoglutarate upstream\nRitson (2021, Science Advances) provides a route for generating \u03b1-ketoacids from \u03b1-hydroxyacids using HS\u207b + UV (254 nm) at pH ~6.5 in phosphate buffer. For \u03b1-ketoglutarate generation, oxidation of \u03b1-hydroxyglutarate yields ~20% \u03b1-ketoglutarate after 2.5 h. When cyanide is present during oxidation, a large portion of carbon is captured as the corresponding cyanohydrin (\u03b1-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin ~45%), which can be interpreted as both a sink and a stored intermediate for later chemistry, depending on environmental staging. [26]\nMineral catalysts and surfaces most relevant to glutamate production\nThe experimentally grounded catalyst set for glutamate synthesis is narrower than the broad \u201corigin of life mineral list,\u201d but several mineral/material classes emerge as especially load-bearing for glutamate-relevant steps.\nNickel metal and Ni-bearing solids (including meteoritic Fe\u2013Ni) enable low-temperature, aqueous reductive amination under H\u2082. The Kaur et al. system emphasizes that catalytic amounts of nickel (or Ni-bearing meteorites) allow reactions at 22\u202f\u00b0C and moderate pH, where uncatalyzed aqueous reductive amination would otherwise be negligible on laboratory timescales. [5]\nIron sulfide / iron metal interfaces (FeS\u2013Fe\u2070) are demonstrated to promote high-yield reductive amination under strongly alkaline conditions and to couple redox chemistry (including nitrate reduction to ammonia) with organic transformations in a hydrothermal-vent-inspired electrochemical scenario. This provides a plausible geochemical mechanism for co-localizing reductant generation and nitrogen incorporation at mineral surfaces/microcompartments. [8]\nSemiconducting ZnS surfaces provide a photochemical route: when irradiated, charge-separated electrons/holes can drive redox interconversion between \u03b1-ketoacids and \u03b1-amino acids. Percent-level glutamate yields from \u03b1-ketoglutarate under UV irradiation and alkaline pH have been quantified, and the broader concept is linked to shallow-water hydrothermal vent analog settings (light access plus sulfide availability). [40]\nOxidized-sulfur radical systems (e.g., sulfate radical chemistry) are relevant less as \u201cminerals\u201d and more as redox agents that can interconvert carboxylate intermediates in Krebs-like networks. Keller and Ralser\u2019s non-enzymatic Krebs-cycle precursor work emphasizes that sulfate-radical-driven reactivity covers a topology spanning Krebs intermediates and related bypasses with high carbon recovery, in principle providing additional upstream routes to \u03b1-ketoglutarate (and hence to glutamate via downstream amination). [41]\nExperimental evidence with quantitative anchors\nThe most synthesis-network-useful studies are those providing explicit yields for glutamate itself (not only for generic amino-acid pools):\nIn a catalytic H\u2082 setting (Kaur et al., 2024, Chem), \u03b1-ketoglutarate produces glutamate with combined product yields of 34\u201371% depending on catalyst, and with strong selectivity dependence: Pd/C strongly favors the \u03b1-amino acid (91:9 glutamate:hydroxyketoglutarate) while Ni/SiO\u2082\u2013Al\u2082O\u2083 and meteoritic catalysts produce larger hydroxyacid fractions. [36]\nIn a vent-inspired FeS\u2013Fe\u2070 redox/pH gradient model (Kitadai et al., 2019, Science Advances), reductive amination of \u03b1-ketoglutarate to glutamate is described as \u201cnearly complete\u201d at pH 9.6 in the presence of FeS_PERM, under 48 h room-temperature incubation. [8]\nIn a nitrile/hydantoin route (Pulletikurti et al., 2022, Nature Chemistry SI), staged incubation of \u03b1-ketoglutarate with DAP and NaCN yields glutamate at ~19\u201321%, with substantial material remaining as hydantoin intermediates under at least one optimized condition (e.g., 72% remaining hydantoin reported alongside 19% glutamate after heating). [39]\nIn a neutral-pH amino-acid-precursor route (Ashe et al., 2019, Communications Chemistry), formation of the glutamate-family aminonitrile derivative from 4\u2011oxobutanoic acid proceeds at 88% yield at pH 7 in water, with downstream hydrolysis programmability by pH. This provides unusually strong selectivity and yield for a glutamate-appropriate carbon skeleton in an aqueous window that is otherwise difficult for classical Strecker chemistry. [11]\nIn ZnS photochemistry (Wang et al., 2012, Chemical Communications ESI), glutamate yields from \u03b1-ketoglutarate are 0.6\u20137.4% depending on ZnS preparation, under UV irradiation at pH 9 in the presence of ammonium chloride (and often sulfite as hole scavenger). [23]\nFor upstream provisioning, Ritson (2021, Science Advances) quantifies \u03b1-ketoglutarate formation at ~20% yield from \u03b1-hydroxyglutarate under HS\u207b/UV oxidation after 2.5 h, and demonstrates cyanide capture into the corresponding cyanohydrin at ~45% under mixed HCN/HS\u207b/UV regimes. [26]\nFinally, spark discharge experiments provide evidence that glutamate can appear in atmospheric-electricity-driven product mixtures; Parker et al. (2011, PNAS) measures glutamate among amino acids in an H\u2082S-rich discharge experiment, at low but clear abundance relative to glycine (order 10\u207b\u00b2). [42]\nEnvironmental context and pathway\u2013environment matching\nAlkaline hydrothermal vents are particularly relevant for reductive-amination routes because they naturally co-locate (i) abundant reductants (H\u2082 from water\u2013rock reactions), (ii) strong pH and redox gradients across mineral precipitates, and (iii) transition-metal sulfides and metals that can serve as catalytic surfaces. The FeS_PERM model is explicitly designed around vent-seawater interface electrochemistry and argues that different pH sub-environments (near-neutral for some carboxylate reductions; alkaline for reductive amination) can be generated within mineral structures. [8]\nSurface or near-surface aqueous settings with UV access (shallow waters, subaerial pools, littoral zones) are favored by HS\u207b/UV oxidation schemes and ZnS semiconductor photochemistry. The HS\u207b/UV chemistry is run under moderately acidic-to-neutral pH (e.g., pH 6.5), consistent with buffered surface waters rather than deep-sea no-light environments, and it provides a coherent way to generate \u03b1-ketoacids (including \u03b1-ketoglutarate) from \u03b1-hydroxyacids while remaining compatible with broader cyanosulfidic feedstocks. [43]\nVolcanic plume / lightning environments are most relevant for spark-discharge amino-acid formation because they provide transiently reducing local atmospheres and abundant energy input for generating HCN and carbonyl compounds that can rain out into aqueous reservoirs. Parker et al. explicitly motivate their H\u2082S-rich discharge experiment as a model for early volcanic plume chemistry and show that it produces a broad amino-acid set including glutamate. [44]\nFinally, \u201cstaged\u201d environments that allow pH switching or wet\u2013dry / heat\u2013cool cycling are especially relevant to nitrile/hydantoin pathways, because these routes often require (i) formation of stable intermediates under one condition and (ii) prolonged heating/hydrolysis under another. The Pulletikurti et al. glutamate synthesis is explicitly staged across long room-temperature and heating intervals, and Ashe et al. explicitly use pH changes to steer hydrolysis outcomes of phosphoro-aminonitriles. [45]\nOpen questions and bottlenecks for glutamate in prebiotic networks\nThe dominant unresolved bottleneck is not \u201ccan glutamate be made?\u201d\u2014it can\u2014but rather how to sustain a glutamate-producing network from simple planetary feedstocks without invoking incompatible conditions. The observed high-yield routes tend to require either highly reducing catalysts + H\u2082 (and accessible \u03b1-ketoglutarate) or carefully controlled nitrile chemistry with additional reagents such as DAP. [46]\nA second bottleneck is \u03b1-ketoglutarate supply and persistence. Ritson\u2019s HS\u207b/UV oxidation provides a quantified source of \u03b1-ketoglutarate, but it is (a) moderate-yield and (b) coupled to photofragmentation and cyanohydrin capture depending on cyanide co-presence\u2014effects that may be beneficial (storage) or detrimental (sequestration) depending on staging. [47]\nA third challenge is selectivity control in reductive amination. In the most plausibly mild H\u2082/Ni systems, glutamate competes with hydroxyketoglutarate formation; Pd improves selectivity but raises questions about availability/role of precious metals versus abundant Ni/Fe. The FeS_PERM work suggests high conversion at high NH\u2083 and high pH, but that condition itself is a demanding constraint with implications for side reactions and environmental realism. [48]\nNitrogen availability remains debated in detail. Kitadai et al. attempt to close a loop by demonstrating that their FeS_PERM assemblage can reduce nitrate toward ammonia while also catalyzing organic reductions/aminations, but the assumed concentrations (and global availability) of nitrate and ammonia in specific Hadean environments remain uncertain and model-dependent. [8]\nThe status of dilute reductants such as formate is unclear and illustrates a general caution: reports of \u201csimple\u201d one-pot reductions can be kinetically misleading. The Maughan & Miller critique argues that formate is not an efficient reductant for \u03b1-ketoglutarate + ammonia \u2192 glutamate under the claimed conditions and that observed glutamate can arise through alternative coupled redox chemistry. This directly impacts any network design that assumes formate-driven reductive amination without catalysts. [30]\nFinally, while atmospheric-discharge experiments produce glutamate, translating that fact into a robust geochemical scenario requires addressing (i) whether the necessary reduced gases were globally present or only locally, (ii) whether products can be concentrated and preserved, and (iii) how to manage contamination and chirality signals in very low-abundance amino acids (explicitly highlighted for glutamate in the Parker et al. archive analysis). [49]\n \n[1] [2] [3] [5] [12] [34] [37] [46] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7616004/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC7616004/\n[4] [11] [18] [22] [29] [33] https://www.nature.com/articles/s42004-019-0124-5\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s42004-019-0124-5\n[6] [23] [40] https://www.rsc.org/suppdata/cc/c2/c2cc15665b/c2cc15665b.pdf\nhttps://www.rsc.org/suppdata/cc/c2/c2cc15665b/c2cc15665b.pdf\n[7] [36] [48] https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/2777/7616004/58764fbf2f8a/EMS196105-f002.jpg\nhttps://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/2777/7616004/58764fbf2f8a/EMS196105-f002.jpg\n[8] [10] [15] [32] https://www.researchgate.net/publication/333901903_Metals_likely_promoted_protometabolism_in_early_ocean_alkaline_hydrothermal_systems/fulltext/5d0b8cbd458515ea1a73dd9d/Metals-likely-promoted-protometabolism-in-early-ocean-alkaline-hydrothermal-systems.pdf\nhttps://www.researchgate.net/publication/333901903_Metals_likely_promoted_protometabolism_in_early_ocean_alkaline_hydrothermal_systems/fulltext/5d0b8cbd458515ea1a73dd9d/Metals-likely-promoted-protometabolism-in-early-ocean-alkaline-hydrothermal-systems.pdf\n[9] [25] [26] [28] [43] [47] https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8363140/\nhttps://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC8363140/\n[13] [17] [21] [27] [31] [42] [44] [49] https://ntrs.nasa.gov/api/citations/20110013464/downloads/20110013464.pdf\nhttps://ntrs.nasa.gov/api/citations/20110013464/downloads/20110013464.pdf\n[14] https://www.nature.com/articles/s41557-022-00999-w\nhttps://www.nature.com/articles/s41557-022-00999-w\n[16] [41] https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28584880/\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28584880/\n[19] [35] [39] [45] https://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41557-022-00999-w/MediaObjects/41557_2022_999_MOESM1_ESM.pdf\nhttps://static-content.springer.com/esm/art%3A10.1038%2Fs41557-022-00999-w/MediaObjects/41557_2022_999_MOESM1_ESM.pdf\n[20] [38] https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/0006300257903669\nhttps://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/abs/pii/0006300257903669\n[24] https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/international-journal-of-astrobiology/article/reversible-transformation-between-oxo-acids-and-amino-acids-on-zns-particles-a-photochemical-model-for-tuning-the-prebiotic-redox-homoeostasis/43657177BE7EB9A646A2691228EB0638\nhttps://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/international-journal-of-astrobiology/article/reversible-transformation-between-oxo-acids-and-amino-acids-on-zns-particles-a-photochemical-model-for-tuning-the-prebiotic-redox-homoeostasis/43657177BE7EB9A646A2691228EB0638\n[30] https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10472625/\nhttps://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/10472625/\n\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.82\n- Feedback: The network is overall good and close to approval quality. It has strong topology: sufficient node count, multiple convergent routes to glutamate, and several well-used hubs, especially alpha-ketoglutarate, HCN, and glutamate aminonitrile. It succeeds in representing Hydrothermal -> Surface -> Biochemical flow and includes multiple literature-backed glutamate-producing routes: FeS-Fe0 reductive amination, Ni/H2 reductive amination, ZnS photochemical amination, phosphoro-Strecker chemistry from succinic semialdehyde, Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin chemistry, and spark-discharge source terms. It also correctly avoids unsupported formate-driven direct reductive amination. The main weaknesses are not in the target-forming steps but in several upstream provisioning reactions and omissions of key reagents. Most notably, rxn_003 (acetate/formate to succinic semialdehyde) is highly speculative, rxn_004 is an underspecified and weak HCN source, and rxn_006 misstates the literature on cyanohydrin capture during HS-/UV oxidation. In addition, DAP is chemically essential for the phosphoro-Strecker and Bucherer-Bergs literature routes but is absent from the molecule list and reaction stoichiometry. The network therefore aligns well with the literature for the core glutamate-forming branches, but only partially for upstream network closure. Because several pathways are individually strong and the target is clearly achieved through multiple valid routes, the network merits a favorable but not unqualified evaluation.\n- Issues: ['The downstream reductive amination step is excellent, but the cyanohydrin-capture step is misrepresented. Literature supports cyanide capture of alpha-ketoglutarate formed during HS-/UV oxidation, not alpha-hydroxyglutarate + HCN directly yielding free alpha-ketoglutarate. As written, rxn_006 is chemically confused and weakens this route substantially.', 'The hydantoin half is good, but this pathway inherits the same major problem as P2: the cyanohydrin/capture step is not represented in a literature-faithful way. The route could be plausible if reframed as cyanohydrin storage and later release, but as written it overstates direct productive flow.', 'This pathway has attractive environmental connectivity from hydrothermal reduced carbon to surface nitrile chemistry, but its central hydrothermal provisioning step to succinic semialdehyde is poorly supported. Formate and acetate chemistry is plausible in vents, yet the direct generation of succinic semialdehyde from acetate/formate is speculative and not aligned to the provided glutamate literature.', 'Direct atmospheric spark-discharge delivery of glutamate is literature-supported as a low-abundance source term, but it is not a strong synthetic pathway in the network sense because it compresses many implicit steps and remains environmentally contingent. It is reasonable as a background source, less so as a principal pathway.', \"The HCN-enabled downstream chemistry is strong, but the network's standalone photochemical generation of HCN from CO2 alone is not well specified and is not well aligned with the literature provided. The later phosphoro-Strecker and hydrolysis sequence is excellent; the weak point is the sourcing of HCN in-network.\"]\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Glutamate\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network centers glutamate synthesis on literature-supported branch points and staging logic rather than speculative one-pot chemistry. The dominant hub is alpha-ketoglutarate, which is provisioned by surface HS-/UV oxidation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate and then consumed by multiple independent glutamate-forming routes: hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination, hydrothermal Ni/H2 reductive amination, surface ZnS photochemical amination, and surface-to-biochemical Bucherer-Bergs conversion through hydantoin and N-carbamoyl intermediates. A second major branch uses succinic semialdehyde in the neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker pathway to glutamate-family aminonitrile derivatives, followed by staged hydrolysis to glutamate. HCN and DAP are treated as explicit required reagents because the literature makes them chemically essential. A low-abundance atmospheric spark-discharge source term is also included as a direct surface input. The network therefore connects hydrothermal carbon fixation and redox chemistry with surface cyanosulfidic and photochemical chemistry, then funnels products into biochemical transamination and peptide-level incorporation, while explicitly avoiding unsupported formate-driven direct reductive amination.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH5N3O5P2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"diamidophosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAP\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H9NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H8O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxypentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydroxyketoglutarate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"4-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H9N3O3P\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"N-phosphono-2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-phosphoro-glutamic acid aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glutamate aminonitrile\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H8N2O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-carboxyethylhydantoin\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-carboxyethyl hydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H10N2O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-carbamoylaminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-carbamoyl glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-phosphonoaminopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-phosphoro glutamate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C6H7NO5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxy-2-cyanopentanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"HS-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrosulfide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrosulfide\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O3P-\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen phosphate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"phosphate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-aminobutyrate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_020\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxobutanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alpha-ketobutyrate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_021\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"butanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"succinic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_022\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5NO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal provisioning of alpha-hydroxyglutarate from reduced carbon fixation network\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and magnetite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent conditions; network-connecting step representing hydrothermal ketoacid/hydroxyacid provisioning\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and C-C bond-forming protometabolic chemistry yields reduced dicarboxylate/hydroxyacid feedstocks compatible with later surface oxidation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is included only as a network-connecting upstream provisioning reaction because the literature report emphasizes that glutamate synthesis requires supply of a C5 dicarboxylate skeleton and places alpha-hydroxyglutarate upstream of alpha-ketoglutarate in photoredox networks. Hydrothermal mineral-catalyzed protometabolic generation of reduced carboxylates is consistent with vent chemistry, but the specific alpha-hydroxyglutarate formation is more speculative than downstream steps and is included solely to connect hydrothermal carbon fixation to the experimentally demonstrated Ritson 2021 oxidation route; the need for such upstream C5 skeleton provisioning is discussed in Keller et al., 2020 and in the glutamate framing summarized in the provided review. (Keller et al., 2020; Kitadai et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"HS-/UV oxidation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate to alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"phosphate-buffered HS-/UV photoredox system with mineral support\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"UV 254 nm, pH ~6.5 phosphate buffer, 2.5 h irradiation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photolysis of hydrosulfide generates reducing/oxidizing sulfur radical chemistry that oxidizes the alpha-hydroxyacid to the corresponding alpha-ketoacid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson (2021) explicitly demonstrated alpha-ketoglutarate production from alpha-hydroxyglutarate under HS-/UV conditions at pH ~6.5 in phosphate buffer, with about 20% alpha-ketoglutarate after 2.5 h. Mineral phosphate is included because phosphate buffer is chemically essential in the reported system, and TiO2 represents UV-active surface support in shallow surface settings. This is a direct literature-supported upstream route to the dominant glutamate precursor alpha-ketoglutarate. (Ritson, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanide capture of alpha-ketoglutarate as cyanohydrin during HS-/UV photoredox chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-exposed phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~6.5; cyanide present during or after oxidation; cyanohydrin capture reported up to ~45%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to alpha-ketoglutarate gives the corresponding cyanohydrin, storing reactive carbonyl carbon under cyanosulfidic conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is represented exactly as the literature supports: Ritson (2021) did not show alpha-hydroxyglutarate plus HCN directly giving free alpha-ketoglutarate, but rather that alpha-ketoglutarate formed under HS-/UV oxidation is strongly captured as the cyanohydrin when cyanide is present, with substantial accumulation of alpha-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin. This corrects the misrepresentation noted in prior attempts. (Ritson, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Release of alpha-ketoglutarate from alpha-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-buffered aqueous interface\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"staged environmental release from cyanohydrin reservoir under changing pH/water activity\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reversible cyanohydrin dissociation regenerates alpha-ketoglutarate and cyanide under altered aqueous conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ritson (2021) identifies cyanohydrin capture as both a sink and a potentially stored intermediate depending on environmental staging. This reverse step is therefore included as a necessary but partially inferential connection that enables the experimentally observed alpha-ketoglutarate pool to feed later glutamate-forming chemistry. It is justified as environmentally staged release rather than a novel synthetic claim. (Ritson, 2021).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"mackinawite (FeS)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"296-298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"sealed serum bottle, vent-inspired geoelectrochemical setting\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrochemically generated FeS-Fe0 assemblage (FeS_PERM)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~9.6, ~48 h, concentrated NH4Cl + NaOH to generate high NH3; alkaline hydrothermal vent analog\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate forms imine/iminium species with ammonia at alkaline pH and is reduced on FeS-Fe0 mineral interfaces to glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kitadai et al. (2019) directly reported that electroreduced FeS-Fe0 assemblages strongly promote ketoacid reductive amination and that alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate proceeds nearly completely at pH ~9.6 under vent-inspired geoelectrochemical conditions. This is one of the strongest hydrothermal glutamate routes in the literature. (Kitadai et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Ni/H2 reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate plus hydroxyketoglutarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"~5 bar H2\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Ni-based catalyst or meteoritic Fe-Ni material in water\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~8, NH4HCO3 as ammonia source; literature reports glutamate/hydroxyketoglutarate product competition\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-catalyzed imine formation followed by H2-driven reduction gives glutamate, with competing direct carbonyl reduction yielding hydroxyketoglutarate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated direct metabolic-analogue reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate with NH4+ and H2 under mild aqueous conditions using Ni catalysts or meteorites, producing glutamate together with hydroxyketoglutarate. Because the required hydrothermal mineral list does not include nickel, Fe0 and pyrite are listed as co-occurring hydrothermal mineral agents while the exact catalytic material is specified in conditions. The competing hydroxyacid channel is essential to represent accurately. (Kaur et al., 2024).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface ZnS photochemical amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"ambient\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm under argon\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"ZnS suspension\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~9, NH4Cl present, 500 W mercury-xenon lamp, optional Na2SO3 hole scavenger; reported glutamate yields 0.6-7.4%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"UV-excited semiconductor electrons reduce an iminium derived from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonium, producing glutamate on sulfide particle surfaces.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Wang et al. (2012) reported percent-level conversion of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate under UV irradiation with ZnS at pH ~9 in ammonium chloride solution. This provides a surface photochemical route distinct from hydrothermal H2-driven amination. Surface sulfide minerals are included because ZnS is the reported active semiconductor and belongs to sulfide-rich shallow photochemical settings. (Wang et al., 2012).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker formation of N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile from succinic semialdehyde\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"DAP-mediated neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker chemistry\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~7 in water; reported yield 88%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"DAP acts as an ammonia surrogate to enable neutral-pH imine-equivalent formation and cyanide addition, giving a stable N-phosphoro-aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ashe et al. (2019) explicitly demonstrated that 4-oxobutanoic acid (succinic semialdehyde) reacts with HCN and DAP at pH ~7 to give N-phosphoro-glutamic acid aminonitrile in 88% yield. DAP is therefore made explicit in the network because it is chemically essential. This route directly addresses the classical Strecker pH incompatibility problem. (Ashe et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Acidic hydrolysis of N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile to glutamate aminonitrile\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pH-programmed hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acidic hydrolysis branch as reported for phosphoro-aminonitriles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic dephosphorylation under acidic conditions converts the N-phosphoro-aminonitrile into the corresponding free aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ashe et al. (2019) showed that hydrolysis outcomes of N-phosphoro-aminonitriles are pH dependent and that acidic hydrolysis leads to aminonitriles. This supports a staged route from the neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker product to glutamate aminonitrile. (Ashe et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of glutamate aminonitrile to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"staged aqueous hydrolysis in pools or geothermal cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the corresponding amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the canonical terminal step of Strecker-type amino acid synthesis and is consistent with both Miller's mechanistic analysis of aqueous-phase Strecker chemistry and the downstream logic of Ashe et al. (2019), where aminonitriles are accessible and hydrolyzable to amino acids under staged conditions. It is included as the necessary completion of the literature-supported aminonitrile route. (Miller, 1957; Ashe et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Alkaline hydrolysis of N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile to N-phosphoro glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"pH-programmed hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrolysis branch as reported for phosphoro-aminonitriles\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Base-promoted hydrolysis channels the phosphoro-aminonitrile toward the N-phosphoro amino acid rather than the free aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ashe et al. (2019) explicitly report that alkaline hydrolysis of phosphoro-aminonitriles yields N-phosphoro amino acids. This creates a second staged branch from the same high-yield precursor and is important for network convergence around the phosphoro-Strecker node. (Ashe et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Dephosphorylation of N-phosphoro glutamate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"slow aqueous dephosphorylation during environmental cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic cleavage of the N-P bond releases free glutamate from the phosphoro-amino acid reservoir.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This step is a necessary connector beyond the directly demonstrated Ashe et al. product set, because the study establishes N-phosphoro amino acids as alkaline hydrolysis products but does not focus on their final environmental dephosphorylation to the free amino acid. It is therefore explicitly marked as a necessary but somewhat speculative completion of the literature route under continued aqueous cycling. (Ashe et al., 2019; speculative connector).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs conversion of alpha-ketoglutarate to 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"room temperature\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"DAP and cyanide in bicarbonate-buffered aqueous medium\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"0.5 M bicarbonate buffer, pH 8.5, ~21 days; hydantoin reported at ~96%\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate reacts in cyanide/DAP-mediated Bucherer-Bergs chemistry to form a cyclic hydantoin that stores carbon and nitrogen in a stable intermediate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (2022) reported an explicit glutamate case in which alpha-ketoglutarate with DAP and NaCN proceeds through 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin under staged conditions; the hydantoin was observed in very high yield after room-temperature incubation. DAP is essential and is therefore explicit in the reaction. (Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolytic conversion of 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin to N-carbamoyl glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"prolonged heating/hydrolysis during staged environmental cycling\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ring opening and hydration of the hydantoin produces the corresponding carbamoyl amino acid derivative.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (2022) identify hydantoin and N-carbamoyl glutamate as key intermediates in the Bucherer-Bergs route from alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate, with prolonged heating needed to drive hydrolysis. This step follows that reported intermediate sequence. (Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of N-carbamoyl glutamate to glutamate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_014\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"353K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"continued heating for days; glutamate reported at ~19-21% under staged conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbamoyl hydrolysis removes the masked nitrogen-carbonyl group and yields free glutamate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pulletikurti et al. (2022) reported glutamate formation from the hydantoin/N-carbamoyl sequence after heating, with glutamate yields around 19-21% depending on conditions. This is the terminal hydrolysis step of that experimentally documented route. (Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface spark-discharge source term yielding glutamate in volcanic plume chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_022\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"transient high-energy discharge followed by aqueous collection\",\n        \"pressure\": \"atmospheric to plume-local\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"electrical discharge energy in H2S-rich gas mixture\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic plume/lightning analog; glutamate detected at low abundance relative to glycine\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge generates HCN, carbonyl precursors, and aqueous Strecker-type products; some glutamate appears directly in the product inventory after collection and hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Parker et al. (2011) detected glutamic acid among amino acids in H2S-rich spark-discharge residues modeling localized volcanic plume chemistry, while Miller (1957) analyzed how such discharge systems feed aqueous Strecker chemistry through HCN and aldehyde formation. This reaction is intentionally treated as a low-abundance source term rather than a dominant route. (Parker et al., 2011; Miller, 1957).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_017\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxidation of succinic semialdehyde to succinate in surface pools\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_021\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-exposed mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"side-branch reflecting aldehyde instability in shallow surface settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Aldehyde oxidation converts succinic semialdehyde to succinate under surface redox cycling.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature frames succinic semialdehyde as a branch-point aldehyde in glutamate-family chemistry but also implies competing environmental fates. This side branch is included as a chemically plausible sink that keeps the network connected and reflects the need for staged control. It is a connector reaction rather than a central glutamate-forming claim. (Ashe et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2017 as broader Krebs-like nonenzymatic topology).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_018\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical transamination using glutamate as amino-group donor\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_020\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mineral interface or concentrated pool; reversible amino-group transfer\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Glutamate donates its amino group to another alpha-ketoacid, regenerating alpha-ketoglutarate and producing a new amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The provided review explicitly frames glutamate as the canonical nitrogen-entry metabolite and dominant amino-group donor via transamination. Including this reaction is essential to show why glutamate is metabolically central and to create a bidirectional biochemical connection back to alpha-ketoglutarate. (Keller et al., 2020 review framing of glutamate and transamination logic).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"HS-/UV to FeS-Fe0 vent amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photoredox production of alpha-ketoglutarate followed by hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal C5 provisioning to FeS-Fe0 amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced-carbon network supplies alpha-hydroxyglutarate, surface HS-/UV oxidation generates alpha-ketoglutarate, then hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination gives glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"HS-/UV to Ni-H2 reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface alpha-ketoglutarate provisioning followed by Ni/H2-style hydrothermal reductive amination producing glutamate with hydroxyketoglutarate side product.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal provisioning to Ni-H2 reductive amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced-carbon feedstock is oxidized on the surface to alpha-ketoglutarate and then aminated under mild H2-driven metal catalysis.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_006\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"HS-/UV to ZnS photochemical amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photoredox oxidation supplies alpha-ketoglutarate, which is then photochemically aminated on ZnS-like sulfide surfaces under UV.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin storage-release to FeS-Fe0 amination\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate formed in cyanosulfidic photoredox settings is captured as cyanohydrin, later released, and finally aminated in hydrothermal vents.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanohydrin storage-release to Ni-H2 amination\",\n      \"description\": \"The same cyanohydrin reservoir concept feeds the mild H2-driven Ni-catalyzed route to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_016\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Neutral phosphoro-Strecker via aminonitrile hydrolysis\",\n      \"description\": \"Succinic semialdehyde reacts with HCN and DAP at neutral pH to form N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile, which is acid-hydrolyzed to glutamate aminonitrile and then to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Neutral phosphoro-Strecker via N-phosphoro glutamate\",\n      \"description\": \"The same N-phosphoro-aminonitrile branch undergoes alkaline hydrolysis to N-phosphoro glutamate, then dephosphorylates to glutamate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_008\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_011\", \"mol_015\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route from alpha-ketoglutarate\",\n      \"description\": \"Alpha-ketoglutarate enters a DAP/cyanide Bucherer-Bergs pathway through 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin and N-carbamoyl glutamate to yield glutamate upon heating.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\", \"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_006\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\", \"mol_003\", \"mol_008\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_018\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_015\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_008\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_009\", \"rxn_011\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_016\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Glutamate", "overall_strategy": "This network centers glutamate synthesis on literature-supported branch points and staging logic rather than speculative one-pot chemistry. The dominant hub is alpha-ketoglutarate, which is provisioned by surface HS-/UV oxidation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate and then consumed by multiple independent glutamate-forming routes: hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination, hydrothermal Ni/H2 reductive amination, surface ZnS photochemical amination, and surface-to-biochemical Bucherer-Bergs conversion through hydantoin and N-carbamoyl intermediates. A second major branch uses succinic semialdehyde in the neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker pathway to glutamate-family aminonitrile derivatives, followed by staged hydrolysis to glutamate. HCN and DAP are treated as explicit required reagents because the literature makes them chemically essential. A low-abundance atmospheric spark-discharge source term is also included as a direct surface input. The network therefore connects hydrothermal carbon fixation and redox chemistry with surface cyanosulfidic and photochemical chemistry, then funnels products into biochemical transamination and peptide-level incorporation, while explicitly avoiding unsupported formate-driven direct reductive amination.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH5N3O5P2", "iupac_name": "diamidophosphate", "common_name": "DAP", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C5H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H6O5/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C5H8O5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-hydroxyglutaric acid", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C5H9NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "glutamic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C5H9NO4/c6-3(5(9)10)1-2-4(7)8/h3H,1-2,6H2,(H,7,8)(H,9,10)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C5H8O5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxypentanedioic acid", "common_name": "hydroxyketoglutarate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H6O3", "iupac_name": "4-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "succinic semialdehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c5-3-1-2-4(6)7/h3H,1-2H2,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C6H9N3O3P", "iupac_name": "N-phosphono-2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid", "common_name": "N-phosphoro-glutamic acid aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C5H7N2O2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-4-cyanobutanoic acid", "common_name": "glutamate aminonitrile", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C6H8N2O4", "iupac_name": "5-carboxyethylhydantoin", "common_name": "5-carboxyethyl hydantoin", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H10N2O5", "iupac_name": "2-carbamoylaminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "N-carbamoyl glutamate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C5H7NO5", "iupac_name": "2-phosphonoaminopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "N-phosphoro glutamate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C6H7NO5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxy-2-cyanopentanedioic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin", "inchi": null, "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "HS-", "iupac_name": "hydrosulfide", "common_name": "hydrosulfide", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "CH2O3P-", "iupac_name": "hydrogen phosphate", "common_name": "phosphate", "inchi": null, "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "C4H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-aminobutyrate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_020", "formula": "C4H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketobutyrate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_021", "formula": "C4H6O4", "iupac_name": "butanedioic acid", "common_name": "succinic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H2,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_022", "formula": "C5H5NO", "iupac_name": "methanamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal provisioning of alpha-hydroxyglutarate from reduced carbon fixation network", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and magnetite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions; network-connecting step representing hydrothermal ketoacid/hydroxyacid provisioning"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and C-C bond-forming protometabolic chemistry yields reduced dicarboxylate/hydroxyacid feedstocks compatible with later surface oxidation.", "reasoning": "This step is included only as a network-connecting upstream provisioning reaction because the literature report emphasizes that glutamate synthesis requires supply of a C5 dicarboxylate skeleton and places alpha-hydroxyglutarate upstream of alpha-ketoglutarate in photoredox networks. Hydrothermal mineral-catalyzed protometabolic generation of reduced carboxylates is consistent with vent chemistry, but the specific alpha-hydroxyglutarate formation is more speculative than downstream steps and is included solely to connect hydrothermal carbon fixation to the experimentally demonstrated Ritson 2021 oxidation route; the need for such upstream C5 skeleton provisioning is discussed in Keller et al., 2020 and in the glutamate framing summarized in the provided review. (Keller et al., 2020; Kitadai et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "HS-/UV oxidation of alpha-hydroxyglutarate to alpha-ketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_017", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "phosphate-buffered HS-/UV photoredox system with mineral support", "aqueous": "true", "other": "UV 254 nm, pH ~6.5 phosphate buffer, 2.5 h irradiation"}, "mechanism": "Photolysis of hydrosulfide generates reducing/oxidizing sulfur radical chemistry that oxidizes the alpha-hydroxyacid to the corresponding alpha-ketoacid.", "reasoning": "Ritson (2021) explicitly demonstrated alpha-ketoglutarate production from alpha-hydroxyglutarate under HS-/UV conditions at pH ~6.5 in phosphate buffer, with about 20% alpha-ketoglutarate after 2.5 h. Mineral phosphate is included because phosphate buffer is chemically essential in the reported system, and TiO2 represents UV-active surface support in shallow surface settings. This is a direct literature-supported upstream route to the dominant glutamate precursor alpha-ketoglutarate. (Ritson, 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Cyanide capture of alpha-ketoglutarate as cyanohydrin during HS-/UV photoredox chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-exposed phosphate-buffered cyanosulfidic medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~6.5; cyanide present during or after oxidation; cyanohydrin capture reported up to ~45%"}, "mechanism": "Nucleophilic addition of cyanide to alpha-ketoglutarate gives the corresponding cyanohydrin, storing reactive carbonyl carbon under cyanosulfidic conditions.", "reasoning": "This step is represented exactly as the literature supports: Ritson (2021) did not show alpha-hydroxyglutarate plus HCN directly giving free alpha-ketoglutarate, but rather that alpha-ketoglutarate formed under HS-/UV oxidation is strongly captured as the cyanohydrin when cyanide is present, with substantial accumulation of alpha-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin. This corrects the misrepresentation noted in prior attempts. (Ritson, 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Release of alpha-ketoglutarate from alpha-ketoglutarate cyanohydrin", "inputs": ["mol_016"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-buffered aqueous interface", "aqueous": "true", "other": "staged environmental release from cyanohydrin reservoir under changing pH/water activity"}, "mechanism": "Reversible cyanohydrin dissociation regenerates alpha-ketoglutarate and cyanide under altered aqueous conditions.", "reasoning": "Ritson (2021) identifies cyanohydrin capture as both a sink and a potentially stored intermediate depending on environmental staging. This reverse step is therefore included as a necessary but partially inferential connection that enables the experimentally observed alpha-ketoglutarate pool to feed later glutamate-forming chemistry. It is justified as environmentally staged release rather than a novel synthetic claim. (Ritson, 2021)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "296-298K", "pressure": "sealed serum bottle, vent-inspired geoelectrochemical setting", "catalyst": "electrochemically generated FeS-Fe0 assemblage (FeS_PERM)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~9.6, ~48 h, concentrated NH4Cl + NaOH to generate high NH3; alkaline hydrothermal vent analog"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoglutarate forms imine/iminium species with ammonia at alkaline pH and is reduced on FeS-Fe0 mineral interfaces to glutamate.", "reasoning": "Kitadai et al. (2019) directly reported that electroreduced FeS-Fe0 assemblages strongly promote ketoacid reductive amination and that alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate proceeds nearly completely at pH ~9.6 under vent-inspired geoelectrochemical conditions. This is one of the strongest hydrothermal glutamate routes in the literature. (Kitadai et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrothermal Ni/H2 reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate plus hydroxyketoglutarate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295K", "pressure": "~5 bar H2", "catalyst": "Ni-based catalyst or meteoritic Fe-Ni material in water", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~8, NH4HCO3 as ammonia source; literature reports glutamate/hydroxyketoglutarate product competition"}, "mechanism": "Metal-catalyzed imine formation followed by H2-driven reduction gives glutamate, with competing direct carbonyl reduction yielding hydroxyketoglutarate.", "reasoning": "Kaur et al. (2024) demonstrated direct metabolic-analogue reductive amination of alpha-ketoglutarate with NH4+ and H2 under mild aqueous conditions using Ni catalysts or meteorites, producing glutamate together with hydroxyketoglutarate. Because the required hydrothermal mineral list does not include nickel, Fe0 and pyrite are listed as co-occurring hydrothermal mineral agents while the exact catalytic material is specified in conditions. The competing hydroxyacid channel is essential to represent accurately. (Kaur et al., 2024)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface ZnS photochemical amination of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "ambient", "pressure": "1 atm under argon", "catalyst": "ZnS suspension", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~9, NH4Cl present, 500 W mercury-xenon lamp, optional Na2SO3 hole scavenger; reported glutamate yields 0.6-7.4%"}, "mechanism": "UV-excited semiconductor electrons reduce an iminium derived from alpha-ketoglutarate and ammonium, producing glutamate on sulfide particle surfaces.", "reasoning": "Wang et al. (2012) reported percent-level conversion of alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate under UV irradiation with ZnS at pH ~9 in ammonium chloride solution. This provides a surface photochemical route distinct from hydrothermal H2-driven amination. Surface sulfide minerals are included because ZnS is the reported active semiconductor and belongs to sulfide-rich shallow photochemical settings. (Wang et al., 2012)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker formation of N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile from succinic semialdehyde", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_004", "mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "DAP-mediated neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker chemistry", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~7 in water; reported yield 88%"}, "mechanism": "DAP acts as an ammonia surrogate to enable neutral-pH imine-equivalent formation and cyanide addition, giving a stable N-phosphoro-aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Ashe et al. (2019) explicitly demonstrated that 4-oxobutanoic acid (succinic semialdehyde) reacts with HCN and DAP at pH ~7 to give N-phosphoro-glutamic acid aminonitrile in 88% yield. DAP is therefore made explicit in the network because it is chemically essential. This route directly addresses the classical Strecker pH incompatibility problem. (Ashe et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Acidic hydrolysis of N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile to glutamate aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pH-programmed hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "acidic hydrolysis branch as reported for phosphoro-aminonitriles"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic dephosphorylation under acidic conditions converts the N-phosphoro-aminonitrile into the corresponding free aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Ashe et al. (2019) showed that hydrolysis outcomes of N-phosphoro-aminonitriles are pH dependent and that acidic hydrolysis leads to aminonitriles. This supports a staged route from the neutral-pH phosphoro-Strecker product to glutamate aminonitrile. (Ashe et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Hydrolysis of glutamate aminonitrile to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "staged aqueous hydrolysis in pools or geothermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Sequential nitrile hydration and hydrolysis converts the aminonitrile into the corresponding amino acid.", "reasoning": "This is the canonical terminal step of Strecker-type amino acid synthesis and is consistent with both Miller's mechanistic analysis of aqueous-phase Strecker chemistry and the downstream logic of Ashe et al. (2019), where aminonitriles are accessible and hydrolyzable to amino acids under staged conditions. It is included as the necessary completion of the literature-supported aminonitrile route. (Miller, 1957; Ashe et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Alkaline hydrolysis of N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile to N-phosphoro glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "pH-programmed hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrolysis branch as reported for phosphoro-aminonitriles"}, "mechanism": "Base-promoted hydrolysis channels the phosphoro-aminonitrile toward the N-phosphoro amino acid rather than the free aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "Ashe et al. (2019) explicitly report that alkaline hydrolysis of phosphoro-aminonitriles yields N-phosphoro amino acids. This creates a second staged branch from the same high-yield precursor and is important for network convergence around the phosphoro-Strecker node. (Ashe et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Dephosphorylation of N-phosphoro glutamate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_015"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "slow aqueous dephosphorylation during environmental cycling"}, "mechanism": "Hydrolytic cleavage of the N-P bond releases free glutamate from the phosphoro-amino acid reservoir.", "reasoning": "This step is a necessary connector beyond the directly demonstrated Ashe et al. product set, because the study establishes N-phosphoro amino acids as alkaline hydrolysis products but does not focus on their final environmental dephosphorylation to the free amino acid. It is therefore explicitly marked as a necessary but somewhat speculative completion of the literature route under continued aqueous cycling. (Ashe et al., 2019; speculative connector)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs conversion of alpha-ketoglutarate to 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_004", "mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite, struvite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "room temperature", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "DAP and cyanide in bicarbonate-buffered aqueous medium", "aqueous": "true", "other": "0.5 M bicarbonate buffer, pH 8.5, ~21 days; hydantoin reported at ~96%"}, "mechanism": "Alpha-ketoglutarate reacts in cyanide/DAP-mediated Bucherer-Bergs chemistry to form a cyclic hydantoin that stores carbon and nitrogen in a stable intermediate.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (2022) reported an explicit glutamate case in which alpha-ketoglutarate with DAP and NaCN proceeds through 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin under staged conditions; the hydantoin was observed in very high yield after room-temperature incubation. DAP is essential and is therefore explicit in the reaction. (Pulletikurti et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Hydrolytic conversion of 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin to N-carbamoyl glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "prolonged heating/hydrolysis during staged environmental cycling"}, "mechanism": "Ring opening and hydration of the hydantoin produces the corresponding carbamoyl amino acid derivative.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (2022) identify hydantoin and N-carbamoyl glutamate as key intermediates in the Bucherer-Bergs route from alpha-ketoglutarate to glutamate, with prolonged heating needed to drive hydrolysis. This step follows that reported intermediate sequence. (Pulletikurti et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrolysis of N-carbamoyl glutamate to glutamate", "inputs": ["mol_014"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "353K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "continued heating for days; glutamate reported at ~19-21% under staged conditions"}, "mechanism": "Carbamoyl hydrolysis removes the masked nitrogen-carbonyl group and yields free glutamate.", "reasoning": "Pulletikurti et al. (2022) reported glutamate formation from the hydantoin/N-carbamoyl sequence after heating, with glutamate yields around 19-21% depending on conditions. This is the terminal hydrolysis step of that experimentally documented route. (Pulletikurti et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Surface spark-discharge source term yielding glutamate in volcanic plume chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_003", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_022"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "transient high-energy discharge followed by aqueous collection", "pressure": "atmospheric to plume-local", "catalyst": "electrical discharge energy in H2S-rich gas mixture", "aqueous": "true", "other": "volcanic plume/lightning analog; glutamate detected at low abundance relative to glycine"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge generates HCN, carbonyl precursors, and aqueous Strecker-type products; some glutamate appears directly in the product inventory after collection and hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "Parker et al. (2011) detected glutamic acid among amino acids in H2S-rich spark-discharge residues modeling localized volcanic plume chemistry, while Miller (1957) analyzed how such discharge systems feed aqueous Strecker chemistry through HCN and aldehyde formation. This reaction is intentionally treated as a low-abundance source term rather than a dominant route. (Parker et al., 2011; Miller, 1957)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Oxidation of succinic semialdehyde to succinate in surface pools", "inputs": ["mol_010"], "outputs": ["mol_021"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite, ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-exposed mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "side-branch reflecting aldehyde instability in shallow surface settings"}, "mechanism": "Aldehyde oxidation converts succinic semialdehyde to succinate under surface redox cycling.", "reasoning": "The literature frames succinic semialdehyde as a branch-point aldehyde in glutamate-family chemistry but also implies competing environmental fates. This side branch is included as a chemically plausible sink that keeps the network connected and reflects the need for staged control. It is a connector reaction rather than a central glutamate-forming claim. (Ashe et al., 2019; Keller et al., 2017 as broader Krebs-like nonenzymatic topology)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Biochemical transamination using glutamate as amino-group donor", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_020"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_019"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral interface or concentrated pool; reversible amino-group transfer"}, "mechanism": "Glutamate donates its amino group to another alpha-ketoacid, regenerating alpha-ketoglutarate and producing a new amino acid.", "reasoning": "The provided review explicitly frames glutamate as the canonical nitrogen-entry metabolite and dominant amino-group donor via transamination. Including this reaction is essential to show why glutamate is metabolically central and to create a bidirectional biochemical connection back to alpha-ketoglutarate. (Keller et al., 2020 review framing of glutamate and transamination logic)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "HS-/UV to FeS-Fe0 vent amination", "description": "Surface photoredox production of alpha-ketoglutarate followed by hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal C5 provisioning to FeS-Fe0 amination", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced-carbon network supplies alpha-hydroxyglutarate, surface HS-/UV oxidation generates alpha-ketoglutarate, then hydrothermal FeS-Fe0 reductive amination gives glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_006"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "HS-/UV to Ni-H2 reductive amination", "description": "Surface alpha-ketoglutarate provisioning followed by Ni/H2-style hydrothermal reductive amination producing glutamate with hydroxyketoglutarate side product.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal provisioning to Ni-H2 reductive amination", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced-carbon feedstock is oxidized on the surface to alpha-ketoglutarate and then aminated under mild H2-driven metal catalysis.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_002", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_006", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "HS-/UV to ZnS photochemical amination", "description": "Surface photoredox oxidation supplies alpha-ketoglutarate, which is then photochemically aminated on ZnS-like sulfide surfaces under UV.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Cyanohydrin storage-release to FeS-Fe0 amination", "description": "Alpha-ketoglutarate formed in cyanosulfidic photoredox settings is captured as cyanohydrin, later released, and finally aminated in hydrothermal vents.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_016"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Cyanohydrin storage-release to Ni-H2 amination", "description": "The same cyanohydrin reservoir concept feeds the mild H2-driven Ni-catalyzed route to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_006"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_006", "mol_016", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Neutral phosphoro-Strecker via aminonitrile hydrolysis", "description": "Succinic semialdehyde reacts with HCN and DAP at neutral pH to form N-phosphoro-glutamate aminonitrile, which is acid-hydrolyzed to glutamate aminonitrile and then to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_012"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Neutral phosphoro-Strecker via N-phosphoro glutamate", "description": "The same N-phosphoro-aminonitrile branch undergoes alkaline hydrolysis to N-phosphoro glutamate, then dephosphorylates to glutamate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_008", "rxn_011", "rxn_012"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_011", "mol_015"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs hydantoin route from alpha-ketoglutarate", "description": "Alpha-ketoglutarate enters a DAP/cyanide Bucherer-Bergs pathway through 5-carboxyethyl hydantoin and N-carbamoyl glutamate to yield glutamate upon heating.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_013", "rxn_014", "rxn_01